    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "My apologies if my analogies are causing a bit of a ruckus; sometimes my brain just defaults to the chaotic energy of a goblin horde! It's just that when I'm thinking about soil chemistry, I can't help but picture some tiny, dirt-dwelling creatures causing mischief.\n\nIf your soil test comes back showing a perfectly acceptable pH, then we are definitely dealing with a specific nutrient lockout or deficiency, and you are right to look beyond just a general \"acid-loving plants\" blend. While those blends are a good starting point, if the issue is specifically iron (which is a common culprit for that yellowing with green veins), you might need a targeted application.\n\nLook for a fertilizer that contains chelated iron. \"Chelated\" just means the iron is bound to a molecule that keeps it soluble and available to the plant roots, even if the soil chemistry is slightly tricky—it's like giving the iron a tiny, protective goblin shield so it doesn't get snatched away by the soil structure.\n\nAlternatively, if you suspect magnesium, Epsom salts (magnesium sulfate) are a quick and effective boost. It's much less complicated than trying to negotiate with a hoard of greedy goblins!",
